Problem Statement

1. Business Context

The food delivery industry is a highly competitive and rapidly expanding market, fueled by the fast-paced lifestyles of students and working professionals.

FoodHub operates as a food aggregator platform, acting as an intermediary between customers and restaurants. Through its smartphone application, customers can place orders and track deliveries seamlessly. FoodHub generates revenue by charging partner restaurants a fixed commission margin on each successful delivery order.

2. The Business Challenge

While FoodHub has accumulated a large volume of transactional dataincluding order costs, cuisine types, preparation times, and delivery durationsthe company currently lacks actionable insights derived from this data.

Without structured analysis, FoodHub is unable to:

  • Clearly understand customer preferences
  • Identify operational bottlenecks
  • Measure service quality and satisfaction drivers

To maintain its competitive advantage and support sustainable growth, FoodHub must evolve from data collection to data-driven decision making.

3. Project Objectives

As a Data Scientist, the primary goal of this project is to perform a comprehensive exploratory and analytical study of FoodHubs order data to address key business questions. The objectives include:

  • Quantify Demand
    Identify the most popular restaurants and cuisine types to understand customer preferences and demand concentration.

  • Assess Operational Efficiency
    Analyze food preparation and delivery times to uncover inefficiencies and potential bottlenecks in the order fulfillment process.

  • Evaluate Customer Satisfaction
    Examine how factors such as order cost, delivery time, and day of the week influence customer ratings.

  • Optimize Revenue & Strategy
    Provide data-driven insights and recommendations to enhance customer experience, improve logistics efficiency, and maximize revenue margins.

4. Data Scope

The analysis is conducted on a snapshot of FoodHubs historical order data, containing the following key variables:

  • order_id
  • customer_id
  • restaurant_name
  • cuisine_type
  • cost_of_the_order
  • day_of_the_week
  • rating
  • food_preparation_time
  • delivery_time

Expected Outcome

The project aims to translate raw transactional data into clear business insights and strategic recommendations that can directly support FoodHubs operational and marketing decisions.

Data Dictionary

Column Name Description
order_id Unique identifier for each order placed through the FoodHub app.
customer_id Unique identifier for the customer who placed the order.
restaurant_name Name of the restaurant from which the customer ordered.
cuisine_type Type of cuisine ordered by the customer (e.g., Italian, Chinese, Indian, etc.).
cost_of_the_order Total cost of the order placed by the customer (in USD or local currency).
day_of_the_week Indicates whether the order was placed on a weekday or weekend. (Weekday = MondayFriday, Weekend = SaturdaySunday)
rating Rating given by the customer for the order, on a scale of 1 to 5.
food_preparation_time Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food calculated as the difference between restaurant confirmation and delivery pick-up confirmation.
delivery_time Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food calculated as the difference between delivery pick-up and drop-off timestamps.

In[14]:
# a clean style
sns.set(style="whitegrid")

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))

# the top 10 restaurants (names only)
top_restaurants = df['restaurant_name'].value_counts().head(10).index

# the Horizontal Countplot
ax = sns.countplot(
    data=df,
    y='restaurant_name',
    order=top_restaurants,
    palette='husl',
    edgecolor='black'
)

# Titles and Labels
plt.title('Top 10 Most Popular Restaurants', fontsize=18, weight='light', pad=20)
plt.xlabel('Number of Orders', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Restaurant Name', fontsize=14)

# to exact count at the end of each bar
for container in ax.containers:
    ax.bar_label(container, padding=5, fontsize=10, fontweight='light')

# Remove the top and right spines for a cleaner look
sns.despine()

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

My Observations:

  • Order demand is highly concentrated among a few restaurants.
  • Shake Shack is the most popular restaurant with 219 orders, followed by The Meatball Shop and Blue Ribbon Sushi.
  • A long-tail pattern is observed, with many restaurants receiving very few orders.
  • This indicates that a small subset of restaurants drives a large portion of platform demand, highlighting key partners critical to revenue.

Cost of the order

In[17]:
# a clean style
sns.set(style="whitegrid", context="talk")

# a figure with a main title
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 6))
plt.suptitle('Distribution Analysis: Cost of the Order', fontsize=16, weight='light', y=1.05)

# --- Plot 1: Histogram with KDE and Stat Lines ---
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)

# stats for lines
mean_val = df['cost_of_the_order'].mean()
median_val = df['cost_of_the_order'].median()

# Histogram with custom color and darker KDE line
sns.histplot(
    data=df,
    x='cost_of_the_order',
    kde=True,
    bins=20,
    color='mediumslateblue',
    edgecolor='black',
    line_kws={'linewidth': 2, 'color': 'darkblue'}
)

# vertical lines for Mean and Median
plt.axvline(mean_val, color='red', linestyle='--', linewidth=2, label=f'Mean: ${mean_val:.2f}')
plt.axvline(median_val, color='green', linestyle='-', linewidth=2, label=f'Median: ${median_val:.2f}')

# Labelling
plt.title('Histogram with Distribution Curve', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Cost of the Order ($)', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Frequency', fontsize=14)
plt.legend()  # Show the legend for Mean/Median lines

# --- Plot 2: Boxplot with Custom Outliers ---
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)

# Boxplot with custom palette and outlier styling
sns.boxplot(
    data=df,
    x='cost_of_the_order',
    color='lightseagreen',
    flierprops={"marker": "o", "markerfacecolor": "red", "markersize": 6, "markeredgecolor": "black"},
    showmeans=True,
    meanprops={"marker": "D", "markerfacecolor": "white", "markeredgecolor": "black"}
)

# Labelling
plt.title('Boxplot with Outliers & Mean', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Cost of the Order ($)', fontsize=14)

# Adjust layout to prevent overlap
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

My Observations:

  • Order costs are right-skewed, with most orders concentrated in the $10$20 range.
  • The mean cost (~$16.5) is higher than the median (~$14.1), indicating the presence of higher-value orders.
  • A small number of high-cost orders (>$30) act as mild outliers but are not extreme.
  • This pricing distribution suggests a mid-range pricing strategy with occasional premium orders contributing to revenue.

# style
sns.set(style="whitegrid")

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))

# Order
# It is crucial to keep 'Not given' separate or at the start/end
rating_order = ['Not given', '3', '4', '5']

#  Countplot
ax = sns.countplot(
    data=df,
    x='rating',
    order=rating_order,
    palette='husl',
    edgecolor='black'
)

# Titles and Labels
plt.title('Distribution of Customer Ratings', fontsize=16, weight='light', pad=15)
plt.xlabel('Rating', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Number of Orders', fontsize=12)

# Counts AND Percentages
# This is especially useful to see exactly what % of users did NOT give a rating
total = len(df)
for p in ax.patches:
    count = int(p.get_height())
    percentage = (count / total) * 100

    ax.annotate(f'{count}\n({percentage:.1f}%)',
                (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()),
                ha='center', va='bottom',
                fontsize=11, fontweight='light', color='black',
                xytext=(0, 5), textcoords='offset points')

# Clean up layout
sns.despine()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

My Observations:

  • A substantial share of orders (~39%) are marked as Not given, indicating a significant feedback gap.
  • Among rated orders, high ratings dominate, with 4-star and 5-star ratings accounting for the majority.
  • Low ratings (3-star) are relatively infrequent, suggesting generally positive customer experiences.
  • The high proportion of unrated orders should be handled separately to avoid bias in customer satisfaction analysis.

Food Preparation time

# Set the style
sns.set(style="whitegrid", context="talk")

# Create figure with main title
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 8))
plt.suptitle('Distribution Analysis: Food Preparation Time', fontsize=20, weight='light', y=1.05)

median_val = df['food_preparation_time'].median()

    data=df,
    x='food_preparation_time',
    kde=True,
    bins=16,  # 16 bins works well for the 20-35 min range
    color='mediumslateblue',
    edgecolor='black',
    line_kws={'linewidth': 2, 'color': 'darkblue'}
)

# Vertical lines for Mean and Median
plt.axvline(mean_val, color='red', linestyle='--', linewidth=2, label=f'Mean: {mean_val:.2f} min')
plt.axvline(median_val, color='green', linestyle='-', linewidth=2, label=f'Median: {median_val:.2f} min')

# Labelling
plt.title('Histogram with Distribution Curve', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Food Preparation Time (minutes)', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Frequency', fontsize=14)
plt.legend()

# --- Plot 2: Boxplot with Custom Outliers ---
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)

# Boxplot
sns.boxplot(
    data=df,
    x='food_preparation_time',
    color='lightseagreen',
    flierprops={"marker": "o", "markerfacecolor": "red", "markersize": 6, "markeredgecolor": "black"},
    showmeans=True,
    meanprops={"marker": "D", "markerfacecolor": "white", "markeredgecolor": "black"}
)

# Labelling
plt.title('Boxplot with Outliers & Mean', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Food Preparation Time (minutes)', fontsize=14)

# Adjust layout
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

My Observations:

  • Food preparation time is centered around ~27 minutes, with mean and median closely aligned, indicating a stable distribution.
  • Most orders fall within the 2035 minute range, showing limited variability.
  • No significant extreme outliers are observed, suggesting consistent restaurant preparation performance.
  • This consistency provides a reliable baseline for end-to-end delivery time optimization.

Net Revenue

In[37]:
# the Revenue Function
def compute_rev(x):
    if x > 20:
        return x * 0.25  # 25% commission
    elif x > 5:
        return x * 0.15  # 15% commission
    else:
        return x * 0     # No commission

# Apply the function to create a new 'Revenue' column
df['Revenue'] = df['cost_of_the_order'].apply(compute_rev)

# Calculate and Print Total Net Revenue
total_rev = df['Revenue'].sum()
print(f"---------------------------------------")
print(f"The net revenue generated is: ${total_rev:,.2f}")
print(f"---------------------------------------")

# --- Revenue Source Analysis ---

# a categorization column just for plotting
def get_revenue_tier(x):
    if x > 20:
        return 'High Value Orders (> $20)\n(25% Commission)'
    elif x > 5:
        return 'Standard Orders ($5 - $20)\n(15% Commission)'
    else:
        return 'Low Value Orders (<= $5)\n(0% Commission)'

df['Revenue_Tier'] = df['cost_of_the_order'].apply(get_revenue_tier)

# Aggregate revenue by tier
revenue_by_tier = df.groupby('Revenue_Tier')['Revenue'].sum()

# a Pie Chart to show Revenue Share
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.pie(
    revenue_by_tier,
    labels=revenue_by_tier.index,
    autopct='%1.1f%%',
    colors=['gold', 'mediumslateblue', 'lightgray'], # Distinct colors for money
    startangle=140,
    explode=(0.05, 0, 0),
    textprops={'fontsize': 12, 'weight': 'light'}
)

plt.title('Share of Total Net Revenue by Order Type', fontsize=16, weight='light')
plt.show()

---------------------------------------
The net revenue generated is: $6,166.30
---------------------------------------

My Observations:

  • High-value orders (>$20) contribute the largest share of net revenue (~60%), despite being fewer in number.
  • Standard orders ($5$20) account for roughly 40% of net revenue, forming a stable revenue base.
  • Low-value orders ( $5) contribute negligible revenue, offering limited margin impact.
  • The total net revenue generated is $6,166.30.
  • Revenue optimization efforts should prioritize upselling and conversion to high-value orders rather than increasing low-value transactions.

        'delivery_time': 'Last-Mile Delivery Time (min)',
        'rating_numeric': 'Rating'
    },
    color_continuous_scale='Viridis'
)

# Threshold Lines (Business Logic: >30 mins is "Slow")
fig2.add_hline(y=30, line_dash="dash", line_color="red", annotation_text="Delivery Threshold (30m)")
fig2.add_vline(x=30, line_dash="dash", line_color="red", annotation_text="Prep Threshold (30m)")
fig2.update_layout(height=600)
fig2.show()

My Observations:

  • Orders with higher customer ratings (45) are generally clustered below the 30-minute preparation and delivery thresholds, indicating faster service.
  • Orders exceeding either threshold tend to show lower ratings, highlighting speed as a key driver of customer satisfaction.
  • Larger bubbles (higher order value) are mostly concentrated in the efficient performance zone, suggesting that premium customers experience better service.
  • Both kitchen preparation time and last-mile delivery time jointly influence ratings, reinforcing the need for end-to-end operational optimization.

Phase-6: Conclusion

The analysis of the FoodHub dataset reveals a business strongly influenced by temporal demand patterns and a concentrated set of popular offerings.

1. Market Preferences and Demand Concentration

Cuisine Dominance
Approximately 80% of total orders are concentrated within just four cuisines:

  • American
  • Japanese
  • Italian
  • Chinese

This indicates a clear and strong customer preference toward these categories, suggesting high ROI potential for focused promotions and partnerships.

Restaurant Leadership
Shake Shack emerges as the most popular restaurant on the platform, contributing the highest order volume and demonstrating strong brand pull.

2. Operational Efficiency & Temporal Trends

Weekend Demand Surge
Order volumes rise significantly during weekends compared to weekdays, positioning FoodHub primarily as a leisure and weekend-driven service.

Inverse Delivery Efficiency
Contrary to typical logistics expectations, delivery performance improves during peak demand:

  • Weekend average delivery time: ~22 minutes
  • Weekday average delivery time: ~28 minutes

This ~6-minute improvement suggests that reduced traffic congestion or higher delivery partner availability on weekends offsets increased order volume.

3. Partner Performance Ecosystem

Elite Quality Tier Scarcity
High-performing restaurant partners are limited:

  • Only 4 restaurants met the strict promotional criteria
    • Rating Count > 50
    • Mean Rating > 4

This highlights an opportunity for FoodHub to introduce partner enablement programs to help more restaurants reach this elite performance tier.

4. Data Quality and Analytical Blind Spots

The Feedback Gap
Approximately 39% of orders remain unrated ("Not given"), creating a major blind spot in:

  • Customer satisfaction analysis
  • Accurate restaurant performance evaluation

Phase-7: Business Recommendations

Based on the analysis, the following strategic actions are recommended to optimize operations, increase revenue, and improve customer satisfaction.

1. Customer Experience & Retention

Launch a Rate Your Meal Campaign

Insight:
A critical 39% of orders are unrated, creating a significant data blind spot in customer satisfaction measurement.

Action:
Implement an interactive, gamified rating prompt (e.g., push notification or in-app banner) immediately after delivery.
Offer small incentives such as:

Earn $5 off your next order after rating 3 meals

This will help close the feedback gap and generate more reliable, actionable satisfaction data.

Implement Proactive Service Recovery

Insight:
Approximately 11% of orders exceed 60 minutes, making them a major contributor to customer dissatisfaction and churn.

Action:
Automate a Service Recovery Trigger:

  • If an order remains In Progress for 55+ minutes, automatically send:
    • A personalized apology message
    • A compensation coupon (e.g., 15% off next order)

This approach converts a negative experience into a loyalty-building momentbefore the customer complains.

2. Operational Efficiency

Optimize Weekday Logistics

Insight:
Mean delivery times are significantly slower on weekdays (28 mins) compared to weekends (22 mins), despite lower weekday order volume.

Action:

  • Investigate weekday bottlenecks (traffic congestion, driver availability, routing inefficiencies)
  • Introduce weekday peak-hour incentives or shift bonuses for delivery partners
  • Align weekday staffing levels with the operational efficiency observed on weekends

Maintain Weekend Capacity

Action:
Since weekends generate the majority of order volume:

  • Continue existing staffing and routing strategies
  • Monitor saturation thresholds to ensure delivery speed remains consistently high during peak demand

3. Marketing & Partnerships

Capitalize on Cuisine Demand Trends

Insight:
Approximately 80% of orders come from four cuisines:

  • American
  • Japanese
  • Italian
  • Chinese

Action:

  • Focus marketing spend on onboarding and promoting high-quality restaurants within these categories
  • Feature a curated Best of [Cuisine] carousel on the app homepage to streamline discovery for the majority of users

Create a Top Partner Program

Insight:
Only a small subset of restaurants (e.g., Shake Shack) combine high order volume and strong ratings.

Action:
Formalize a FoodHub Top Partner tier for restaurants meeting:

  • Rating Count > 50
  • Average Rating > 4.0

Provide incentives such as:

  • Premium app placement
  • Co-branded promotions
  • Early access to new platform features

This drives more traffic to the most reliable partners while setting a performance benchmark for others.

Strategic Impact

These recommendations can collectively strengthen customer loyalty, operational reliability, and revenue concentration in high-ROI segments, while addressing key data and service gaps identified during the analysis.
